{
  "texts": [
    "The latter can be provided by simultaneous support and creation of communities of practice (Wenger, 1998) allowing participation in development processes (Moreno-Ger et al., 2008) and knowledge production and transfer between educators, developers, and researchers (Fernández-Manjón et al., 2015; Hébert et al., 2021).",
    "Along a technological dimension, limited accessibility to technology is an issue (Hébert et al., 2021).",
    "Lowering development costs and developing environments that allow educators some game development without requiring substantial programming skills and specific game development expertise are regarded as necessary steps to address this issue (Fernández-Manjón et al., 2015).",
    "In this context, LLMs or more generally generative AI tools have the potential to transform game-based learning practices and-again similarly to the use of computers in Papert's class (1980)-could even become once more part of their own remedy regarding the challenge they pose for education.",
    "This, however, warrants a new pedagogy of learning with artificial intelligence."
  ]
}